GESTURE SWAPPING RULES
When You Can Swap
Rank 1 (Apprentice): Cannot swap. You cast spells as baseline.
Rank 2 (Adept): You perceive the gesture functions of each spell you know. You understand why it works as it does. You cannot yet swap.
Rank 3 (Expert): You can attempt to swap one gesture function in any spell you know. Roll a d20 against your relevant Stat (Magic for most schools). On success, the swapped spell works. On failure, the spell fizzles and you take 1 HP damage from the strain.
Rank 4 (Master): You execute swaps reliably. No roll required. You simply declare which gesture you're swapping and how the spell changes.
The Swap Itself
You can swap any single gesture in a spell. You cannot use the same gesture twice in one spell configuration (no COMMAND + COMMAND).
When you swap:
The Target Number for casting does not change
The FP cost does not change
The base damage or healing does not change
What the spell does changes based on the new gesture configuration
You gain something and lose something (always a trade-off)
Thematic Coherence
Not every swap makes sense. The GM is the final arbiter.
Forbidden Swaps (Examples):
Raise Zombie (COMMAND + BIND) to Raise Zombie (PETITION + BIND) — You cannot petition the dead to return
Invisibility (CONCEAL + RELEASE) to Invisibility (REVEAL + STABILIZE) — Contradictory (can't be hidden and revealed)
Healing Hands (PETITION) to Healing Hands (SEVER) — Doesn't match healing's nature
Allowed But Difficult: Swaps that go against a school's natural affinity can still work, but the GM can mark them as requiring deeper understanding or carrying unusual consequences.


The Three Laws of Modification
The Law of Dilution: If a swap turns a Single-Target spell into an Area of Effect (AoE), the damage is Halved. You cannot gain area coverage without losing intensity.
The Law of Sustain: If a swap (like STABILIZE) changes a Duration to "Concentration" or "Permanent," the caster must spend a Major Action every turn to maintain it. If they take damage, they must make a Magic Save or lose the spell.
The Law of Conservation: A swap cannot replicate the exact effect of a higher-tier spell. (e.g., You cannot swap gestures in Firebolt to make it exactly Fireball). It must remain a variation, not an upgrade.

EXAMPLE SPELL MODIFICATIONS
FIREBALL (Adept: COMMAND + BIND + PROJECT)
Baseline: COMMAND + BIND + PROJECT
Effect: You force fire to explode in a concentrated burst
Area: 20-foot radius sphere
Duration: Instantaneous
Behavior: Explodes at a point, spreads outward
Range: 120 feet
Swap 1: Remove PROJECT, use RELEASE (COMMAND + BIND + RELEASE)
Effect: You force fire to bind in an explosion, then fade
Area: 20-foot radius sphere
Duration: Instantaneous but the fire burns out quickly
Behavior: Explodes once, no lingering effect
Range: 60 feet
Trade-off: Shorter range, no lingering flames, but easier to control (less chaotic)
Swap 2: Replace COMMAND with PETITION (PETITION + BIND + PROJECT)
Effect: You ask fire to manifest as an explosion
Area: 20-foot radius sphere
Duration: Instantaneous
Behavior: Fire gently expands, allies have time to move away
Range: 120 feet
Trade-off: Less chaotic, safer, but allies gain advantage on saving throws
Swap 3: Replace BIND with SHIFT (COMMAND + SHIFT + PROJECT)
Effect: You force fire to arc and spread across distance
Area: 40-foot line, spreads to adjacent targets
Duration: Instantaneous
Behavior: Lightning-like arc, chains to nearby enemies
Range: 180 feet
Trade-off: Larger area but less concentrated, harder to avoid hitting allies
Swap 4: Replace PROJECT with STABILIZE (COMMAND + BIND + STABILIZE)
Effect: You force fire to remain in place
Area: 20-foot radius
Duration: Concentration, up to 10 minutes
Behavior: Burning cloud that persists
Range: 120 feet
Trade-off: No longer instantaneous, requires concentration, but creates persistent hazard

PARALYZE (Apprentice: COMMAND + BIND)
Baseline: COMMAND + BIND
Effect: You force the body to bind itself immobile
Duration: 4 rounds
Behavior: Target cannot move or act
Range: 60 feet
Swap 1: Replace COMMAND with PETITION (PETITION + BIND)
Effect: You ask the body to still itself
Duration: 1 round
Behavior: Target can resist more easily (advantage on saves)
Range: 60 feet
Trade-off: Much weaker and shorter, but target doesn't resist your will as strongly, more negotiation than force
Swap 2: Replace BIND with ANCHOR (COMMAND + ANCHOR)
Effect: You force the target to be anchored to their location
Duration: 4 rounds
Behavior: Target is rooted in place but not paralyzed (can act, cannot move)
Range: 60 feet
Trade-off: Target can still attack/cast, but cannot flee or reposition
Swap 3: Replace BIND with STABILIZE (COMMAND + STABILIZE)
Effect: You force paralysis to become permanent
Duration: Concentration, up to 1 hour
Behavior: Deep paralysis that resists all attempts to break it
Range: 60 feet
Trade-off: Requires your constant concentration, but lasts far longer and resists dispelling
Swap 4: Add ANCHOR (COMMAND + BIND + ANCHOR)
Effect: You force the target to be paralyzed and anchored to their location
Duration: 4 rounds
Behavior: Cannot move, cannot act, rooted to the spot
Range: 60 feet
Trade-off: More powerful effect but requires three gestures (harder for lower-rank casters)

INVISIBILITY (Apprentice: CONCEAL + RELEASE)
Baseline: CONCEAL + RELEASE
Effect: You hide from sight and let the effect fade naturally
Duration: 10 minutes
Behavior: Undetectable, breaks on hostility
Range: Self
Swap 1: Replace RELEASE with BIND (CONCEAL + BIND)
Effect: You hide from sight and lock it in place
Duration: 30 minutes
Behavior: Much harder to break, persists longer
Range: Self
Trade-off: Longer duration but more rigid (can't break it easily yourself if needed)
Swap 2: Replace RELEASE with STABILIZE (CONCEAL + STABILIZE)
Effect: You hide completely and anchor it
Duration: 1 hour, concentration required
Behavior: Nearly impossible to detect, persists through disturbances
Range: Self
Trade-off: Very long duration but you must concentrate the entire time
Swap 3: Replace CONCEAL with REVEAL (REVEAL + RELEASE)
Effect: You become obvious and let it fade
Duration: 5 minutes
Behavior: Everyone sees exactly where you are, becomes less visible as spell fades
Range: Self
Trade-off: Enemies know your location, but spell is easy to cast and breaks easily

HEALING HANDS (Novice: PETITION)
Baseline: PETITION
Effect: You ask the body to heal itself
Healing: 10 HP
Duration: Instantaneous
Range: 30 feet
Swap 1: Replace PETITION with COMMAND (COMMAND)
Effect: You force the body to heal itself
Healing: 15 HP
Duration: Instantaneous
Range: 30 feet
Trade-off: Stronger effect but feels violent to the target, risks damaging trust
Swap 2: Add BIND (PETITION + BIND)
Effect: You ask the wound to seal itself
Healing: 10 HP, but heals twice if cast on same target consecutively
Duration: Instantaneous
Range: 30 feet
Trade-off: Healing persists if cast again, but only works on the same target repeatedly
Swap 3: Add ANCHOR (PETITION + ANCHOR)
Effect: You ask healing to anchor in the target
Healing: 10 HP, plus target gains +1 temporary DR
Duration: Instantaneous
Range: 30 feet
Trade-off: Added benefit but stronger conviction required

THE COLLEGE OF WINTERHOLD AND SOMATIC MASTERY
The College of Winterhold is the center of magical learning in Skyrim. Beyond teaching students how to cast spells, the College preserves and disseminates knowledge about the somatic components—the physical expressions and movements—that underlie all magic.
When you learn a spell through normal magical progression (leveling a school of magic), you know how to cast it. The College teaches you the somatic structure—the underlying components that compose each spell. They preserve grimoires, conduct research, and train scholars who understand not just that magic works, but how it works at a fundamental level.
The College's Academic Mission
The College of Winterhold:
Preserves knowledge of the somatic components underlying all known spells
Teaches students to recognize and understand these components
Allows advanced mages to modify spells by altering their somatic structure
Maintains the largest magical library in Skyrim, including texts on the theory of magic itself
Conducts ongoing research into the nature of magical law and how it can be negotiated with
Learning Somatic Components at the College
When you attend the College, you learn:
The somatic components that compose each spell you know
What each component represents in the magical structure of Skyrim
How to modify spells by changing their somatic components
The theoretical principles that allow this modification to work
This knowledge comes through study with Magisters, consultation of ancient texts, and deep engagement with magical theory. It is not gated by ranks or tests—only by understanding.
When a Magister explains to you that Fireball is built from COMMAND + BIND + PROJECT (three somatic principles), and you understand what those components mean and how they function, you can now modify them. If you swap BIND for SHIFT, you create a new variant where fire adapts and spreads instead of binding in one concentrated explosion.
The Somatic Language
The College has catalogued twelve fundamental somatic components—recurring patterns in how mages physically express and channel magical law. Every spell is built from these components in different combinations.

SCHOOL NATURAL AFFINITIES
Destruction
Natural Components: COMMAND, PROJECT, SEVER, RELEASE
These are easy and intuitive for Destruction mages
Swapping away from these feels unnatural but is still possible
Restoration
Natural Components: PETITION, ANCHOR, STABILIZE, REVEAL
These are easy and intuitive for Restoration mages
Healing magic works through harmony, not force
Alteration
Natural Components: ANCHOR, SHIFT, BIND, STABILIZE
These are easy and intuitive for Alteration mages
Change requires conviction and stability
Conjuration
Natural Components: COMMAND, BIND, PROJECT, ATTUNE
These are easy and intuitive for Conjuration mages
Summoning works through dominance and binding
Illusion
Natural Components: SHIFT, CONCEAL, REVEAL, ATTUNE, RELEASE
These are easy and intuitive for Illusion mages
Illusions work through fluidity and deception
Cross-School Swaps
A Restoration mage swapping PETITION for COMMAND in Healing Hands is doing something thematically weird. The GM can note this:
"You're forcing the body to heal rather than asking it. This feels violent and unnatural."
But it's not forbidden. The mage is learning that magic can be expressed multiple ways. This is advanced understanding, not a violation.

DESIGNING YOUR OWN SOMATIC SWAPS
When a player wants to swap a somatic component, follow this process:
Step 1: Is It Thematically Coherent?
Can you explain the swap in one sentence?
"I'm swapping PROJECT for BIND so Fireball becomes a stationary explosion instead of traveling"
Good. That's coherent.
"I'm swapping COMMAND for REVEAL in Invisibility"
Confused. What does that mean? Work it out with the player.
Step 2: What Changes About the Spell?
Ask yourself: What is different now?
Range? (PROJECT changes reach)
Duration? (BIND/STABILIZE/RELEASE change how long it lasts)
Area? (PROJECT affects larger areas; BIND concentrates it)
Behavior? (SHIFT makes things adaptive; CONCEAL makes things subtle)
Resistance to dispelling? (STABILIZE/BIND resist; RELEASE is fragile)
Step 3: What's the Trade-Off?
Every swap gains something and loses something.
Longer duration = requires concentration or is harder to end
Larger area = less focused effect
More subtle = weaker or harder to notice
More powerful = more obvious/dramatic
Easier to cast = shorter duration or less effective

THE FIVE OUTCOMES WITH SWAPPED SOMATIC COMPONENTS
The Five Outcomes still apply, but they apply to the swapped spell variant, not a "modified outcome."
Critical Success (Roll of 1): The swapped spell works perfectly. Full intended effect with no complications.
Success (Roll under Target Number): The swapped spell works as intended.
Complicated Success (Roll equals Target Number): The swapped spell works, but the complication is tied to the new nature of the spell.
Example: Fireball with STABILIZE works, but the persistent flames are harder to control than expected.
Example: Invisibility with BIND works, but you're more anchored in place than you realized.
Failure (Roll over Target Number): The spell fizzles. No additional cost.
Critical Failure (Roll of 20): The spell backfires. The caster takes 5 HP damage and the spell goes wild.

SUMMARY
The Somatic Component System in One Paragraph:
Every spell is built from somatic components that define its relationship to magical law. By understanding these components, a Master mage can swap one component for another, creating a new variant of the spell. This is not spell invention—it is spell mastery. You don't break the rules; you negotiate with them. The College of Winterhold teaches these components through study and theory, allowing mages who have learned them to modify spells freely. Every swap changes what the spell does without changing its cost or damage. This is how magic deepens in Skyrim.














